Japanese Stocks Climb After U.S. Jobs Report; Bridgestone, Advantest Rise

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-03-03T07:26:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-03/japan-stocks-climb-after-u-s-job-market-report-advantest-elpida-advance.html
Japanese stocks rose as signs of a
strengthening U.S. job market overshadowed concern political
unrest in the Middle East and North Africa will drive energy
costs higher.  Bridgestone Corp., the world’s largest tiremaker, climbed
2.2 percent. Fanuc Corp., an industrial-robot manufacturer that
gets almost 80 percent of its sales overseas, increased 1.2
percent. Advantest Corp., the No. 1 maker of chip-testing
equipment, gained 1.5 percent after JPMorgan Chase & Co. raised
its recommendation on the semiconductor industry.  Okuma Corp. (6103) , a
manufacturer of  machine tools , jumped 6.3 percent after Nomura
Holdings Inc. rated it a “buy.”  “The employment data showed a better-than-expected
improvement and we got confirmation of upward momentum in the  U.S. economy ,” said  Mitsushige Akino , who oversees about $450
million in Tokyo at Ichiyoshi Investment Management Co. “It’s
possible turmoil in the Middle East and North Africa will spread
to  Saudi Arabia  and  Iran , so uncertainty still remains.’  The Nikkei 225 Stock Average rose 0.9 percent to 10,586.02
at the 3 p.m. close in Tokyo. The broader Topix index gained 0.6
percent to 948.69, with about five stocks advancing for every
one that fell. Shares extended gains after a report that
Venezuelan President  Hugo Chavez  called Libyan leader  Muammar
Qaddafi  and offered to help broker peace.  S&P Futures  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index increased as
much as 0.7 percent. The  S&P 500  climbed 0.2 percent yesterday
in New York after a report from ADP Employer Services showed U.S.
employment increased by 217,000 in February, compared with a
median estimate of 180,000 in the Bloomberg News survey.
The  Federal Reserve  separately said the labor market improved
throughout the U.S. early this year, driven by increasing retail
sales and “solid growth” in manufacturing.  Bridgestone rallied 2.2 percent to 1,745 yen. Fanuc
increased 1.2 percent to 12,800 yen. TDK Corp., the world’s No.
1 maker of disk drive heads, gained 0.9 percent to 5,460 yen.  Federal Reserve Chairman Ben S. Bernanke yesterday didn’t
rule out expanding the central bank’s asset purchases aimed at
stimulating the economy, saying he doesn’t want to see the U.S.
relapse into a recession. Bernanke’s comments suggested he will
keep the Fed on course to complete $600 billion of Treasury
purchases through June.  “The market is taking a positive view of the strong
employment figures in the U.S.,” Naoteru Teraoka, general
manager at Tokyo-based Chuo Mitsui Asset Management Co., which
oversees about $26 billion. “Investors are confident that
central banks are going to keep monetary policy loose.”  Oil Dropped  Oil dropped today from the highest close in 29 months in  New York  yesterday, falling as much as 1.8 percent, after the
Wall Street Journal reported  Venezuela  offered to help create a
mediation commission to ease the conflict in  Libya .  The Topix increased 4.9 percent this year through yesterday,
compared with gains of 4 percent by the S&P 500 and 2.5 percent
by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Japanese benchmark
are valued at 15.8 times estimated earnings on average, compared
with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.2 times for the Stoxx 600.  Chip-related companies advanced after JPMorgan named Texas
Instruments Inc. a “top pick” among chipmakers and raised its
recommendation on the industry. The Philadelphia Semiconductor
Index of 30 stocks climbed 1.4 percent yesterday.  Advantest rose 1.5 percent to 1,673 yen. Elpida Memory Inc.,
the No. 3 maker of computer-memory chips, gained 2.3 percent to
1,209 yen. Oki Electric Industry Co., a maker of semiconductors,
climbed 2.9 percent to 72 yen.  Machinery Makers Advance  Okuma jumped 6.3 percent to 798 yen, the biggest gain in
the Nikkei. Nomura yesterday rated Okuma a “buy,” saying the
machine-tool maker will benefit from strong demand in  Asia  and
the U.S., markets where the company gets a combined 52 percent
of sales.  Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd. leapt 5.4 percent to 372
yen, the most since December 2009, after the heavy machinery
maker and Itochu Corp., a trading company, received an order to
supply train cars and equipment for a transit project in Macau.  Softbank Corp., Japan’s third-biggest wireless carrier,
rallied 4.8 percent to 3,410 yen and was the largest single
contributor to gains in the Nikkei and the Topix. Mizuho
Securities Co. reiterated its “outperform” rating on the
shares, saying the carrier isn’t likely to increase its stake in
Yahoo Japan Corp. Softbank declined as much as 4.6 percent
yesterday after Reuters said Yahoo! Inc. of the U.S. may sell
its 35 percent stake in Yahoo Japan.  Nippon Telegraph & Telephone Corp., Japan’s biggest
telecommunications company, climbed 1.5 percent to 4,130 yen,
the highest close since September 2009. JPMorgan reiterated its
“overweight” rating on the company, citing the company’s
forecast for higher profits this year.  To contact the reporters on this story:
